---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About synaplex" description="Why this system exists and how to read it.">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 tracking-tight">About synaplex</h1>

  <div class="prose max-w-2xl">
    <p class="text-lg">
      AI systems have real structure. That structure exists before anyone writes it
      down. synaplex is a feedback system for uncovering it — publicly, durably,
      and with evidence that holds up under adversarial review. We publish to
      <em>discover</em>, not to assert.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">The system, not a publication</h2>
    <p>
      synaplex.ai isn't a blog or a portfolio surface. It is the operational
      substrate of a self-learning feedback loop: canon → knowledge system →
      lab → publication → pods, with signal intake feeding reasoning and
      friction events feeding back into how the system refines itself. The
      public face you are reading is one projection of that system. The
      operator face at <code>command.synaplex.ai</code> is another. Same
      system, different views.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Pods, not sub-brands</h2>
    <p>
      atlas (systematic crypto trading) and skillfoundry (commercial discovery)
      are not products under a synaplex umbrella. They are bidirectional
      exploratory probes of the same underlying methodology — each one
      uncovers invariants that flow into the knowledge system and absorbs
      invariants already in it. Pods have lifecycles. They may emerge,
      explore, contribute, graduate to independence, or deprecate.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Why canon envelopes</h2>
    <p>
      Every lab finding is emitted as a canon envelope conforming to the
      <a href="https://synaplex.ai/discovery-framework/0.1.0/">discovery-framework spec</a> —
      an obligations model (not a state machine) that forces pre-registration,
      typed evidence, cited contradictions, and hash-bound artifacts. Fast blogs
      can out-publish us; they cannot out-replay us. And a publication that
      can be replayed is a publication that can accumulate — each new piece
      building and refining the latent shape rather than being filed behind
      a publish-date.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Editorial independence</h2>
    <p>
      Sponsored evaluations exist and are priced. They use the <em>same</em>
      methodology pipeline as organic ones, run through the <em>same</em>
      adversarial review, and carry a cryptographic
      <code>Policy.provenance.sponsor</code> field in canon so the provenance
      is mechanically inspectable. Sponsors do not get preview or veto over
      findings.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What we won't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>1:1 consulting or audits. Everything we publish is one-to-many.</li>
      <li>Take vendor-provided benchmark numbers at face value.</li>
      <li>Retract an evaluation because a vendor asked politely.</li>
      <li>Bury a negative finding.</li>
      <li>File publications by date. Topology, not timeline.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
